    <segment id="1" parent="18" relname="background">


I work for a large &quot;Fortune 100&quot; company that uses web sites for every imaginable purpose.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="16" relname="span"> The problem is that most of them are so slow</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="2" relname="volitional-result"> one can go get a cup of coffee between queries.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="17" relname="span"> 
I wouldn&apos;t mind the slow queries so much</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="14" relname="span"> if the pages offered status bars to let the user know that a given percentage of the process had been completed.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="15" relname="span"> This would also provide feedback to the user that the click on the web page had actually implemented a function.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="4" relname="elaboration"> Often I am so used to poor query times that I don&apos;t think to make sure that the click on a button or other web logistic actually caused an action.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="17" relname="elaboration"> Yes, status update bars, in my opinion, are crucial to good web site design and implementation.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="19" relname="span"> 
Another area of web page design that causes me problems is when web sites implement their own web buttons for such common things as BACK and HOME.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="13" relname="span"> Why not use the browser provided button for this instead of implementing them in a proprietary manner?</segment>
    <segment id="10" parent="8" relname="elaboration"> Beware the site that boldly announces for the user not to use the browser provided navigation buttons.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="20" relname="volitional-result"> 
Thanks for the opportunity to vent these frustrations.</segment>
